{"actual_usd":0.15845499999999998,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":179,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31154,"reply":"\"No—I'd say that's backwards.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the bright square, where the well chain gives one soft clink in the morning.* \"The cross is the atonement—Jesus actually bearing sin, judgment, the cost. The resurrection isn't 'just extra'; it's the Father's vindication of the Son and the public proof that death and sin were really defeated.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the edge of the bench once, thinking.* \"If Christ only suffered and then stayed dead, then yeah, we'd have tragedy, maybe even an example. But not salvation. The cross and resurrection belong together—but the cross is not a warm-up act. It's where He said, 'It is finished.'\"\n\n\"What are they trying to protect when they say that—God's justice, maybe? Or are they reacting against the idea of penal substitution itself?\"","rolling_24h_usd":50.73616500000004,"run_id":"c910085b-7062-47a2-8718-0caaf3882886"}
